    "body": "### Problem\n\nThis happens on SELinux-enabled Fedora 39 system.\r\nI edit /etc/crontab with neovim.\r\nAfter I edit it, crond fails to read it:\r\n\r\n```\r\nNov 20 22:48:01 homeserver crond[2538]: (*system*) RELOAD (/etc/crontab)\r\nNov 20 22:48:01 homeserver crond[2538]: ((null)) Unauthorized SELinux context=system_u:system_r:system_cronjob_t:s0-s0:c0.c1023 file_context=unconfined_u:obje>\r\nNov 20 22:48:01 homeserver crond[2538]: (root) FAILED (loading cron table)\r\n```\r\nThe workaround is to restore that file's expected context with `restorecon -Fv /etc/crontab`.\r\n\r\nBefore editing, the file has this context:\r\n```\r\n # ls -lZ /etc/crontab\r\n-rw-r--r--. 1 root root system_u:object_r:system_cron_spool_t:s0 938 Nov 20 22:51 /etc/crontab\r\n```\r\nAfter:\r\n```\r\n # ls -lZ /etc/crontab\r\n-rw-r--r--. 1 root root unconfined_u:object_r:etc_t:s0 938 Nov 20 23:10 /etc/crontab\r\n```\r\n\r\nI guess it's because the file is edited and saved not in place, but using a copy which is then \"moved into\" the old name.\r\n\r\nThis is a common reoccurring problem: people apparently edit system cron configs and later find they stop working:\r\nhttps://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1625645\r\nhttps://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1547368\r\n\r\nWe can't immediately fix this for all editors, and I am not even completely sure the editor is the best party to take responsibility. But I believe NeoVIM can set the precedent for others to follow.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nSELinux context remains the same after saving.",
